Oliver:

The spacing looks great, and it works well in both font sizes.  Thanks 
for the time spent improving the kerning.

I hate to be a Johnny one-note, but am I the only person bothered by the 
altered form of &quot;eat&quot; in Kingsley?  Is there some reason the second part 
of the letter cannot be vertical as it is in the manual?  I find it too 
similar to &quot;ooze.&quot;


oliver langan wrote:
&gt;
&gt; When the penis enlargement ads start coming in Shavian and
&gt; Quickscript, we&#39;re really in trouble.
&gt;
&gt; Speaking of which, I spent some time yesterday playing with a font
&gt; editor (I think I have mentioned it before: http://
&gt; fontforge.sourceforge.net/ ) and managed to figure out how to do
&gt; character pair kerning. This has been a huge problem with QS fonts,
&gt; for me at least, since spacing between He and short letters (for
&gt; example) would look as though a space was inserted.
&gt;
&gt; So, I spent some time -- a lot of time actually -- converting the
&gt; &#39;kingsley&#39; font to a) use the conscript unicode block, b) have a
&gt; slightly large space, and c) have much better kerning between the
&gt; letter pairs. The results are really nice, I think:
&gt;
&gt; (attempting to paste an image)
&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; ------------------------------------------------------------------------
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; (smaller version)
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; ------------------------------------------------------------------------
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Note the improved kerning in &#39;you&#39; and &#39;rather&#39; in the first 
&gt; sentence.  Do you think I went overboard with &#39;culture&#39; in the last 
&gt; sentence?
&gt;
The &quot;l&quot; appears too close to the vowel to my eyes.

I also noted that &quot;belongs&quot; is misspelled.  It contains a &quot;t&quot; that 
should not be there.  A few words later, the word &quot;craftwork&quot; is also 
mispelled to my ears - (&quot;on&quot; vowel after &quot;r&quot;).
&gt;
&gt; Using this method, it may be possible to make an almost-senior version 
&gt; of the same font.  In fact, if I can figure out the &#39;alternate glyphs&#39; 
&gt; thing then I might be able to shoehorn half characters in as well.
&gt;
That would be &quot;fantabulous&quot; as Eddie Izzard would say.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; You may notice that the above text is from the QS manual.  My reason 
&gt; for doing this, in fact, is because I am attempting to convert the QS 
&gt; manual so that it might be displayed on the web, using (downloadable) 
&gt; unicode fonts.  The Kingsley font (and jerome too) is a close match 
&gt; for the writing in the manual, but when used to write more than a 
&gt; single word it just looked bad: now it looks much better, and with 
&gt; Unicode it is very easy to intermix quickscript and orthodox.  I will 
&gt; try uploading an in-progress PDF later today, if I am able to verify 
&gt; that it displays correctly on a machine without the font installed 
&gt; (the font is not ready for prime time, and I&#39;d rather sit on it than 
&gt; have lots of different versions out there).
&gt;
&gt; oliver
&gt;

Paige

